*  grant-to-pitch
** Pattern: This Grant Proposal Could Have Been a Consulting Pitch
   + CONTEXT:
     An academic practitioner writes grant proposals that
     demonstrate capability, methodology, and relevance to
     a funder's priorities. The same skill — framing what
     you can do in terms of what the recipient needs — is
     exactly what consulting proposals require.
   + IF:
     The practitioner has experience writing grants (UKRN,
     EPSRC, etc.) and has demonstrable capabilities (Bayesian
     modelling, pattern languages, knowledge management, AI
     integration).
   + HOWEVER:
     Grant proposals go to institutions with long review cycles
     and uncertain outcomes. Consulting pitches go to
     organisations with immediate needs and shorter cycles.
     The same skill applied to the wrong recipient produces
     months of waiting instead of weeks of revenue.
   + THEN:
     For each capability demonstration (working paper, tool,
     methodology), ask: "who would pay for this as a service
     rather than fund it as research?" Reframe the grant
     narrative as a consulting proposal. The Bayesian logic
     model becomes "evaluation consulting." The pattern language
     becomes "structured methodology." The knowledge graph
     becomes "enterprise knowledge management."
   + BECAUSE:
     The fabrication "I need a grant to do this work" dissolves
     when you realise the work is already done and the question
     is who values it. Grants fund potential; consulting pays
     for demonstrated capability. The practitioner who has
     built the stack already has the demonstration.
   + NOTE:
     The inverse also applies: a successful consulting engagement
     generates evidence that strengthens future grant proposals.
     The pattern is bidirectional, not a one-way conversion.
   + RELATED:
     - depositing/scan-talk-frame (daily practice of finding recipients)
     - war-machine/cardinal-directions (this converts cargo to depositing)
     - jsdq/carrying-to-depositing (the JSDQ phase transition)
